            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Magnification formulas</h2>
              <p>
                In geometric optics, <strong>magnification</strong> describes
                how much larger or smaller an image appears compared with the
                original object. It can be defined in several equivalent ways.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Linear magnification from sizes</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Linear magnification \(M\) is the ratio of image height to
                  object height:
                </p>
                <p>\[ M = \frac{h_i}{h_o} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(h_o\): object height (or width)</li>
                  <li>\(h_i\): image height (or width)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                If \(|M| &gt; 1\), the image is larger than the object. If \(|M|
                &lt; 1\), the image is reduced.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Linear magnification from distances</h3>
              <p>
                For a thin lens or mirror, magnification can also be written in
                terms of object and image distances:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ M = -\,\frac{d_i}{d_o} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(d_o\): object distance (from lens to object)</li>
                  <li>\(d_i\): image distance (from lens to image)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                The minus sign encodes the <strong>orientation</strong> of the
                image:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  \(M &gt; 0\): image is upright (same orientation as object)
                </li>
                <li>\(M &lt; 0\): image is inverted (flipped upside down)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Total magnification of a microscope</h3>
              <p>
                A compound microscope uses an objective lens and an eyepiece.
                The total magnification is approximately:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ M_{\text{total}} \approx M_{\text{objective}} \times
                  M_{\text{eyepiece}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>For a simple model using focal lengths:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ M_{\text{objective}} \approx \frac{L}{f_o}, \qquad
                  M_{\text{eyepiece}} \approx \frac{D}{f_e} \]
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(L\): tube length of the microscope</li>
                  <li>\(f_o\): focal length of the objective</li>
                  <li>\(f_e\): focal length of the eyepiece</li>
                  <li>
                    \(D\): near point of the eye (often taken as 25&nbsp;cm)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Angular magnification</h3>
              <p>
                For magnifying glasses and telescopes we often use
                <strong>angular magnification</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ M_{\theta} =
                  \frac{\theta_{\text{image}}}{\theta_{\text{object}}} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  where \(\theta\) is the angle under which the eye sees the
                  object or image.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use this magnification calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose a tab</strong> based on the information you
                  have:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <em>Size-based</em> if you know object and image sizes.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <em>Distance-based</em> if you know object and image
                      distances from a lens or mirror.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <em>Microscope / Telescope</em> if you know lens
                      magnifications or focal lengths.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter your values</strong> using any convenient units
                  (the calculator handles unit consistency within each tab).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Calculate”</strong> to see the magnification
                  and a short interpretation (upright/inverted,
                  enlarged/reduced).
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>
              <h3>Example 1 – Image size on a camera sensor</h3>
              <p>
                A 20&nbsp;mm tall object is imaged as a 5&nbsp;mm tall image on
                a sensor.
              </p>
              <p>\[ M = \frac{h_i}{h_o} = \frac{5}{20} = 0.25 \]</p>
              <p>
                The image is 0.25× the size of the object (a reduction by a
                factor of 4).
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Lens magnification from distances</h3>
              <p>
                An object is placed 200&nbsp;mm from a converging lens. The real
                image forms 50&nbsp;mm on the other side.
              </p>
              <p>\[ M = -\frac{d_i}{d_o} = -\frac{50}{200} = -0.25 \]</p>
              <p>
                The image is 0.25× the size of the object and inverted (negative
                sign).
              </p>

              <h3>Example 3 – Microscope total magnification</h3>
              <p>You use a 40× objective and a 10× eyepiece.</p>
              <p>\[ M_{\text{total}} = 40 \times 10 = 400 \]</p>
              <p>The microscope provides 400× total magnification.</p>

              <h2>Interpreting magnification values</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>\(M = 1\): image and object are the same size.</li>
                <li>\(|M| &gt; 1\): image is larger (enlargement).</li>
                <li>\(|M| &lt; 1\): image is smaller (reduction).</li>
                <li>\(M &gt; 0\): image is upright.</li>
                <li>\(M &lt; 0\): image is inverted.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>What is magnification?</h3>
              <p>
                Magnification is the ratio of the size or apparent size of an
                image to the size of the original object. In optics it is
                usually written as \(M = h_i / h_o\) or \(M = -d_i / d_o\).
              </p>

              <h3>What does a negative magnification mean?</h3>
              <p>
                A negative magnification indicates that the image is inverted
                relative to the object. This is typical for real images formed
                by a single converging lens or mirror.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I calculate total magnification of a microscope?</h3>
              <p>
                Multiply the magnification of the objective lens by the
                magnification of the eyepiece. For example, a 10× eyepiece and
                40× objective give 400× total magnification.
              </p>

              <h3>Is higher magnification always better?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Very high magnification can exceed the resolving power of
                the optics, making the image blurry, dim or shaky. Resolution,
                numerical aperture, lens quality and stability all limit useful
                magnification.
              </p>

              <h3>
                What is the difference between linear and angular magnification?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Linear magnification compares physical sizes of object and
                image. Angular magnification compares the angles under which the
                eye sees the object with and without the instrument, and is used
                for magnifying glasses and telescopes.
              </p>
